    excerpt: "I was twenty-two when a headache told me I was dying.",
    body: "I was twenty-two when a headache told me I was dying.\n\nIt started on an airplane. In 2018 I flew to New York to see Asi Wind — a magician whose work I love — at the release party for his book, _Repertoire_. It was one of the best weekends I'd had in years: close-up magic, a room full of people who speak the only language I'm fluent in, the craft I'd given my life to, all in one place. A transformative weekend, in the small true sense of the word. Then I flew home, and somewhere in the change of cabin pressure a headache set in and did not leave. Not the kind you sleep off. The kind that follows you into a dark room and waits.\n\nI gave it a week. People give headaches a week. When it didn't break, someone made me go in, and the scans came back, and a man I had just met used a word I didn't know: pineoblastoma. Grade four. The high one. The kind they don't usually open the skull for.\n\nHere is the part I think about. If I had not taken those flights, the headache would not have come. Without the headache I would not have gone in. The tumor would have kept growing in the dark, quiet and unhurried, until it reached the brainstem and stopped me in my sleep. The thing that scared me is the thing that found it in time.\n\nI don't have a tidy lesson about that. I didn't earn it. I wasn't owed it. A change in air pressure on a flight I almost didn't take is the only reason I'm here to write this down. People want survival to be a verb you perform. Mostly it's weather.\n\nThey treated me at Florida Hospital South. It's AdventHealth now — same building, new name. I still drive past it.\n\nI was uninsured. I'll get to what that cost. For now there is just the plain fact, set down the way it happened: I got on a plane a healthy young man, and I got off it carrying something that was going to kill me, and the headache it gave me is the reason it didn't.\n\nI got lucky. I want to be honest that it was luck, and not a thing I did.",
