    body: "I measure hard things against one thing now.\n\nWhen something goes wrong — the car dies, the money's short, the show empties out, a person leaves — I ask how bad it is on a scale of one to brain cancer. Brain cancer is the ten. Everything since has been weighed against the year I was told I had months.\n\nIn eight years I have not hit a five.\n\nThis is not a motivational line. It is closer to a measuring tape than a flag. The flat tire is a two. The bounced payment is a three. The night the tour didn't sell and I drove home with the windows down doing the math is maybe a four, and even that, against the ten, is a thing you can carry.\n\nIt does something quieter than make me grateful. It makes me slow. When the ten has already happened, the smaller numbers stop being emergencies. They become weather again — things that pass through, that you stand in, that do not get to decide who you are.\n\nPeople hear this and think it must be freeing. Some days it is. Some days the scale is just another way of saying I have already used up the worst thing, and I am still standing here, tired, doing the math.\n\nBut I'd rather have the scale than not. Most people get handed their ten with no warning and no chance to take its measure. I got mine early, in a sentence, in a room. Everything after has been graded on a curve only I can see.",
